# History: mojo-tensor-design-view-semantics-numeric-correctness

## v1.2.0 (2026-07-11)

**MINOR bump.** Changed-by: ProjectOdyssey #5564 bf16 block-quant reject (PR #5577).
Verification: verified-local (fix + tests run in-container, all pass, proven
non-vacuous; strict-review GO; PR #5577 CI settling — not confirmed merged, so
verified-local not verified-ci).

**What changed:** Added a new dtype-conversion POLICY learning distinct from the
existing bf16-cast pitfalls. `_convert_to_block_quant_impl` (backing
`to_mxfp4()`/`to_nvfp4()`) accepted `bfloat16` in its OUTER floating-point guard, but
the INNER MXFP4/NVFP4 dispatch had no bf16 branch, so bf16 fell through to
`else: raise Error("Invalid dtype for MXFP4 quantization")` — an **accept-then-raise
asymmetry** (outer says yes, inner says no). The design decision was to REJECT bf16 at
the outer guard (not add a support branch), matching the sibling
`_convert_to_fp8_family_impl` in the same file which already rejects bfloat16 with a
documented reason ("the bfloat16 conversion path does not correctly round-trip through
the Float32 intermediate representation"). Adding a widen-bf16→Float32 support branch
would be inconsistent with the FP8/BF8 family and would rely on the exact
Float32-intermediate path the codebase distrusts. Removed the dead inner branch.

**Why:** When a dtype-conversion has an accept-then-raise asymmetry, resolve it by
making the guard consistent with the SIBLING conversion family's established policy —
don't invent a new support path the codebase already rejected elsewhere.

- Added a When-to-Use trigger (accept-then-raise asymmetry).
- Added 3 Failed-Attempts rows (bf16 support branch → reject to match sibling;
  `bitcast[BFloat16]()` → no alias, use `Scalar[DType.bfloat16]`; overclaiming the
  "doesn't round-trip" comment → word it as matched-from-precedent).
- Added a Results row: reject-message pattern + outer-vs-inner test discriminator.
- Honesty note: bf16→Float32 is mathematically an exact widening cast; the
  "doesn't round-trip" justification is really about a Mojo-version-specific bf16 READ
  path being unreliable, not the cast itself. Copy such justifications as
  matched-from-precedent, not independently re-derived.

**Previous version snapshot:** v1.1.0 (2026-06-07), verification verified-ci — the
canonical before this amendment is preserved in the v1.1.0 entry below.

